<!-- SPECIFICATIONS SECTION -->
<h2 style="text-align: center;">Vermicomposting Specifications</h2>
<table border="1" style="width: 100%; text-align: left;">
    <tr>
        <th>Parameters</th>
        <th>Specifications</th>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>01. Monitoring</td>
        <td>Regularly monitor the vermicomposting process by observing the activity of the worms, checking the temperature.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>02. Odour Control</td>
        <td>Properly managed vermicomposting bins should not emit foul odours.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>03. Predator Prevention</td>
        <td>Protect the vermicomposting bins from potential predators such as rodents, ants.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>04. Composting Depth</td>
        <td>Distribute organic waste evenly throughout the bin rather than piling it.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>05. Ventilation</td>
        <td>Adequate ventilation is crucial to prevent the build-up of harmful gases.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>06. Temperature</td>
        <td>Ideal temperature range is from 55℉ to 77℉ (13℃ to 25℃).</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>07. Moisture</td>
        <td>Maintain moisture levels between 60% and 80%.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>08. pH Level</td>
        <td>Aim for a neutral to slightly alkaline pH of 6.0-8.0.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>09. Worm Population</td>
        <td>Maintain an appropriate population of composting worms such as red worms.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        <td>10. Food Scraps</td>
        <td>Offer a variety of fruit and vegetable scraps.</td>
    </tr>
</table>

<hr>

